ce:section.ce:para:
Polypyrrole (PPY), as a conductive polymer, is a promising material to fabricate conductive coatings for protection of metallic bipolar plates (BPs) in proton exchange membrane fuel cells [1,2]. PPY coatings can be electrodeposited onto metal surfaces efficiently at ambient condition, providing physical barriers and anodic protection [3–5]. However, the PPY coatings prepared by electrodeposition exhibited a typical cauliflower-like morphology, which brought defects to the coatings. The metallic BPs work in acidic condition with pH value of 3 at around 80 °C for long term, so they require coatings with corrosion current density (I

                        corr
                     ) of <1 μA cm−2, in addition to high electrical conductivity of >100 S cm−1 and low interfacial contact resistance (ICR) of <10 mΩ cm2 at 140 N cm−2 compaction force for efficient electron conduction in fuel cells [6]. In recent years, efforts have been made to enhance both the corrosion protection properties and the electrical conductivity of the PPY-based coatings.
